@ZaavanMusic There is also a difference between teaching your child and controlling them. If your kid asks for something, do you snap at them or do you explain why they can't have it? When they don't want to eat, do you ask why and show concern, or do you raise your voice to them when they don't comply?

I've had a mix of both in my family, albeit never extreme in either direction, but I've always leaned towards the explanation instead of the punishment. I found out I was neurodivergent only a year ago, as an adult, and looking back I can see that many of my behaviours like being picky, having emotional outbursts and having social problems were a result of that. I am really grateful to my parents that they weren't more forceful, but when I had meltdowns and were slamming doors e.g. they did react forcefully; not with straight up violence, but I was dragged to my room and told to stay there. And that wasn't my fault. I was a kid with a neurological condition neither me nor my parents knew about and it sucks that for a part of my childhood, I was a bit weary of my dad because of it. Whereas, whenever I've gotten things explained to me clearly (the whys and why-nots), then I've been able to adapt much easier.

I don't have children myself, but I have plenty of nieces and nephews and I get glimpses of how much of a challenge it can be to raise children. I also understand that they're your responsibility, you can't just let them starve themselves or accept them skipping school or whatever. But I think control should be the last line of problem solving. I have a niece that has some food problems, and the way her parents solve it is by compromising (one potato and one sausage, then you can go from the table) and keeping an eye out for malnourishment. Turns out, she has eating days and fasting days, basically, and they've been able to work around that. I've always felt that was a very ideal way to deal with the problem. Communication, compromise and comfort. No parents are going to be perfect, obviously, but I think that's something I would aim for if I ever have children.

