Radical honestly is ABSOLUTELY necessary, but in a purely punitive justice system like ours, where an admission of a crime can land a person for life in a dungeon like prison, or for years followed by a life of collateral consequences, that‚Äôs not going to happen. When you back someone into a corner, their only choices are fight or flight. Now, does that mean I think we should give every abuser a pat on the back and high five? Absolutely not. But a more rehabilitative and less punitive (though not entirely non-punitive) system similar to the German or Nordic prisons could increase the likelihood of people coming forward with their abusive behavior. 

With that said, I think we are generally on the same page, and as long as you believe in an abolitionist (or, at least, a carceral system that emphasizes rehabilitation over pure punishment), then I think we don‚Äôt have much to argue about.

@Scoring57¬† I in no way ever implied he needed to be let out of confinement and be allowed to roam free without accountability. I merely stated, like Olay expressed in her video, that prison and the system as it currently stands, will only perpetuate violent acts and behavior in people like ali.

If he doesn't leave prison ever, fine, he's not fit to walk around broader society because he'll hurt someone else again. Now let's mitigate that chance by giving restorative help to people that have caused harm so they don't cause more harm to the people around them. 

And this wouldn't be about forgiveness either. It's a risk benefit analysis that says, hurting criminals doesn't seem to make them stop doing violent acts, but giving them space and mental health seems to make them less violent, so let's do the thing that makes people less violent.
